      <sec sec-type="introduction">
         <title>
Introduction
</title>
         <p>
The genus 
<tp:taxon-name>
Homogryllacris
Liu, 2007
</tp:taxon-name>
currently comprises 27 species, which are distributed in 
China
, 
India
and Southeast Asia (

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; Liu 
et al
., 2021; Liu 
et al
., 2021; 

; 

; Zhang 
et al
., 2023; Zhang 
et al
., 2023; 

, 

). This genus is characterized by male ninth abdominal tergite being without process, tenth abdominal tergite is very short, and the middle of posterior margin has a pair of posterior processes, ovipositor is longer than hind femur, almost straight. As an interesting group, some species of this genus are fully winged, brachypterous and micropterous species also occur.
</p>
         <p>
With its unique natural geographic location and complex and diverse climatic conditions, 
Xizang
is rich in animal and plant resources, it has long been reputed as a rare “green gene pool” and “natural museum” in the world. In recent years, many new species of Ensifera were reported from 
Xizang
by Chinese scholars (Wang 
et al.
, 2012; Wang 
et al.
, 2012; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

).
</p>
         <p>
We examined the 
<tp:taxon-name>
Homogryllacris
</tp:taxon-name>
specimens collected from south 
China
in recent years. Intraspecific variation of 
<tp:taxon-name>
Homogryllacris yunnana
Shi, Guo &amp; Bian, 2012
</tp:taxon-name>
and 
<tp:taxon-name>
Homogryllacris platycis
Liu &amp; Bian, 2021
</tp:taxon-name>
are discussed. Furthermore, on the base of new material collected from 
Xizang
in 
September 2023
, we describe one new species of the genus: 
<tp:taxon-name>
Homogryllacris nigromacula
</tp:taxon-name>
sp. nov.

All specimens examined are deposited in the Museum of 
Hebei
University, Baoding, 
China
.
</p>
         <p>Morphological images were acquired using Leica M205A digital imaging system.Image editing was accomplished using Adobe Photoshop CC 2019. The following conventions were adopted for the specimen measurements: body length—distance from apex of fastigium verticis to posterior margin of ninth abdominal tergite in the midline; pronotum length—distance from anterior to posterior margins of pronotum in the midline; tegmen length—distance of visible part from base of tegmen to the apex; hind femur length—distance from base of hind femur to apex of genicular lobe; ovipositor length—distance from base of subgenital plate to apex of ovipositor.</p>
      </sec>
