            <p>
Description.
Body small-sized for the genus. Head: Face narrow ovoid; fastigium verticis wider than antennal scape. Eyes ovoid, slightly protruding forwards; ocelli distinct, oval. Pronotum short and broad, anterior margin slightly protruding forward, posterior margin straight. Lateral areas of second and third abdominal tergites each with two rows of stridulatory pegs.
</p>
            <p>Wings: squamous, tegmina almost equal to the length of pronotum, nearly reaching posterior margin of first abdominal tergite, with 7 subparallel longitudinal veins; hind wings absent.</p>
            <p>Legs: Fore coxa with 1 spine. Fore and middle femora unarmed on ventral surfaces; fore and middle tibiae with 4 pairs of long spines and 1 pair of short apical spurs on ventral surfaces respectively. Hind femur with 11–12 inner spines and 3–5 outer spines on ventral surface; hind tibia with 6–7 inner spines and 6 outer spines on dorsal surface, bearing 1 pair of dorsal apical spurs and 2 pairs of ventral apical spurs, ventral surface with 1 pair of rather short pre-apical spurs.</p>
            <p>Coloration. Body light brown. Fastigium verticis with dark brown spots; occiput with a large irregular dark brown spot. Inner margin of antennal socket black, base and apex of antennal scape, base of pedicel with dark brown spots, other area of antenna brown. Eyes black. Ocelli light yellow. Face with a longitudinal dark brown stripe in the midline, genae under eyes with a thin black stripe separately, behind eyes each with a dark brown spot. Pronotum with black stripe along entire margin; disc with a broad longitudinal light red stripe; anterior area of disc with a pair of irregular dark brown spots; lateral lobe of pronotum with a broad and irregular dark brown stripe separately. Tegmen semi-transparent with dark brown veins. Metanotum and dorsal surface of abdomen black. Fore femur and tibia light red as well as middle femur and tibia.Apical half of hind femur and hind tibia light red. Posterior processes on male tenth abdominal tergite black. Apical areas of spines and spurs on hind femur and tibia dark brown.</p>
            <p>Male. Ninth abdominal tergite broad at base, gradually narrowing, posterior margin rounded. Tenth abdominal tergite very short, the middle of posterior margin with a pair of robust and short posterior processes, basal halves strongly swollen, apical halves spiniform and crossing each other, pointing ventrad and forwards, tips subacute. Cerci conical and long, apices rounded. Subgenital plate with lateral margins subparallel, posterior margin with a V-shaped incision, lateral lobes with apices rounded. Styli cylindrical with apices rounded, inserted on apical lateral margins of lateral lobes of subgenital plate.</p>
            <p>Female. Appearance is similar to that of male. Seventh abdominal sternite wider than long. Subgenital plate trapezoidal, basal area broad, membranous with transverse folds, posterior margin slightly concave. Ovipositor rather long, much longer than hind femur, almost straight, dorsal and ventral margins subparallel, apex rounded.</p>
